# OminiConnect Portal (the binary loads this file from the **repo root** as `../../.env`)
PORTAL_BASE_URL=http://localhost:9000

# OminiConnect portal database (sqlx Any: SQLite or Postgres).
# Leave DATABASE_URL unset to use SQLite at `omini_connect/portal/portal.db` (stable path regardless of cwd).
# When Nango already uses local Postgres, use a **second database** on the same server (not the same DB as Nango).
#   createdb -h 127.0.0.1 -U nango omini_connect_portal
#   # or: psql -U postgres -c "CREATE DATABASE omini_connect_portal OWNER nango;"
# DATABASE_URL=postgres://nango:nango@127.0.0.1:5432/omini_connect_portal
#
# If you still have an older Postgres database named `omni_portal`, either keep using it in
# DATABASE_URL unchanged, or rename it (disconnect all clients first), e.g.:
#   psql -U postgres -c 'ALTER DATABASE omni_portal RENAME TO omini_connect_portal;'

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Nango (self-hosted, Option B) — OminiConnect talks to Nango over HTTP
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NANGO_BASE_URL — Nango **API** base URL (same as SERVER_PORT in Nango .env).
#   Native dev (no Docker): http://localhost:3003
NANGO_BASE_URL=http://localhost:3003
#
# NANGO_SECRET_KEY — Nango **environment** API secret (Bearer): one value for the whole portal process,
#   not one key per end-user OAuth connection. Nango issues connection_id per link; the portal uses this
#   secret only to call Nango’s HTTP API (sessions, list connections, proxy, etc.).
#   There is no fixed “magic number” shared by all installs — Nango stores a random UUID per environment.
#   **Without the Nango UI:** use ./scripts/sync_nango_secret_to_omini_env.sh (reads Postgres using
#   third_party/nango/.env + NANGO_ENCRYPTION_KEY; seeds a dev account if the DB has no environments).
#   **CI / Kubernetes:** same script with `--print` writes only the secret to stdout, e.g.
#     kubectl create secret generic omini-nango --from-literal=NANGO_SECRET_KEY="$(./scripts/sync_nango_secret_to_omini_env.sh --print)"
#   (run from a Job/init step that can reach Nango’s Postgres and has the Nango .env or equivalent env vars).
#   Manual: Nango UI → Environment → API keys (not LinkedIn/provider client secrets).
#
# Two OminiConnect → two Nango URLs: you need two (NANGO_BASE_URL, NANGO_SECRET_KEY) pairs (one identity per Nango).
#   To simplify ops: run **one** Nango and use **separate Nango environments** (each has its own API key) so every
#   OminiConnect uses the same base URL but a different secret per stage/tenant; or drive both pairs from IaC
#   (Helm values, Terraform) so nothing is hand-pasted per replica.
#
# Kubernetes (many different keys): the portal only reads env vars — configure **one Secret (or ref) per
#   Deployment/Helm release** (e.g. `envFrom.secretRef` or `valueFrom.secretKeyRef`). “Automatic” sync is
#   usually **External Secrets Operator** (pull from AWS Secrets Manager, GCP SM, Vault) or **Sealed Secrets /
#   SOPS** in GitOps — not a feature inside this binary. Replicas of the **same** deployment share one Secret.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# How to run OminiConnect + Nango together (no Docker)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1) Install Node 22+, Rust, PostgreSQL locally. Create **two** databases (same instance is fine), e.g.:
#      createuser nango && psql -U postgres -c "ALTER USER nango WITH PASSWORD 'nango';"
#      createdb -O nango nango
#      createdb -O nango omini_connect_portal
#    Nango uses NANGO_DATABASE_URL in third_party/nango/.env (script defaults to .../nango).
#    OminiConnect uses DATABASE_URL above → point at .../omini_connect_portal when you want Postgres for the portal.
#    Or set before running the script:  export NANGO_DATABASE_URL='postgresql://.../nango'
#
# 2) Repo root:
#      cp .env.example .env
#      # edit DATABASE_URL if using Postgres; set NANGO_* after first Nango UI login
#      make dev
#    First run does `npm ci` + `npm run ts-build` under third_party/nango (slow once).
#
# 3) NANGO_SECRET_KEY: `make dev` auto-writes it from the Nango DB when empty, or run `./scripts/sync_nango_secret_to_omini_env.sh`.
#    Manual path: Nango UI → Environment → API keys, then paste into .env and restart if needed.
#
# Optional — Nango via Docker instead:  make dev-nango-docker
#
NANGO_SECRET_KEY=
